    body: "Spiritual direction is an ancient practice in which a person (the directee) meets regularly with a more experienced guide (the spiritual director) to discuss their prayer life, discern God's movements in their soul, and address obstacles to spiritual growth. It differs from counseling or therapy in that its primary focus is the person's relationship with God rather than psychological health (though the two often overlap). The tradition goes back to the Desert Fathers and Mothers of the 3rd-4th centuries, was systematized by St. John of the Cross and St. Teresa of Avila, and formalized by St. Ignatius of Loyola in his rules for discernment of spirits. Directors help directees recognize consolation and desolation, navigate dark nights of the soul, discern vocational choices, and develop a sustainable prayer life. Good directors listen more than they speak and point always toward God, not toward themselves.",
