    body: "Dominican spirituality (the spirituality of the Order of Preachers, founded by St. Dominic de Guzman in 1216) is summarized in the motto 'Contemplare et contemplata aliis tradere' — to contemplate and to hand on the fruits of contemplation to others. It unites deep intellectual study with prayer, liturgical life, and active preaching. Key elements include: the primacy of truth (Veritas is the Dominican motto), rigorous theological study as a form of prayer, solemn celebration of the Liturgy of the Hours, devotion to the Rosary (which tradition attributes to St. Dominic), community life, and the inseparability of contemplation and apostolate. The Dominican intellectual tradition produced St. Thomas Aquinas, the greatest Catholic theologian, as well as St. Albert the Great, Meister Eckhart, St. Catherine of Siena, and St. Rose of Lima. Dominican preaching aims not merely to inform but to transform through the power of truth encountered in prayer.",
