    oneLiner: "The spiritual tradition of St. Benedict of Nursia, built on the Rule's balance of prayer, work, and community life.",
    body: "Benedictine spirituality is rooted in the Rule of St. Benedict (c. 480-547), the foundational document of Western monasticism. Its guiding principle is 'Ora et Labora' (Pray and Work), reflecting the conviction that holiness is found in the rhythm of daily life rather than in extraordinary feats. Key elements include: the centrality of the Liturgy of the Hours (the Opus Dei or 'Work of God'), lectio divina (meditative reading of Scripture), stability (commitment to one's community and place), conversatio morum (ongoing conversion of life), obedience, hospitality (receiving every guest as Christ), and the balance of prayer, work, study, and rest. The Benedictine motto 'Pax' (Peace) reflects the tranquility of order that characterizes well-lived monastic life. Benedictine monasteries preserved Western civilization through the Dark Ages by copying manuscripts, maintaining schools, and cultivating the land. Oblates of St. Benedict are laypeople who affiliate with a monastery to live this spirituality in the world.",
    example: "The practice of lectio divina — slowly reading a short Scripture passage, meditating on it, praying from it, and resting in God's presence (contemplatio) — originated in Benedictine monasteries and has been widely adopted by Catholics of all states of life as a simple, profound method of prayer.",
    whyItMatters: "Benedictine spirituality offers a remarkably balanced and sustainable approach to holiness. In an age of burnout and fragmentation, its rhythms of prayer and work, silence and community, provide a countercultural wisdom that is more relevant than ever.",
