    oneLiner: "Alternative forms of the Stations of the Cross adapted for different contexts and spiritual emphases.",
    body: "While the traditional fourteen Stations of the Cross have been the standard since the 18th century, numerous approved variations exist within the Catholic tradition. Pope St. John Paul II introduced a Scriptural Way of the Cross in 1991, drawing each station exclusively from events recorded in the Gospels, including the Agony in the Garden and Peter's Denial. Some forms add a fifteenth station for the Resurrection. Other variations include the Via Matris (Way of the Mother), which follows Mary's sorrows alongside her Son, and the Via Lucis (Way of Light), which meditates on fourteen post-Resurrection events from Easter to Pentecost. Franciscan communities have historically been the custodians of the stations and continue to develop forms suited to children, the sick, and particular liturgical seasons.",
