    body: "The Confraternity of the Most Holy Rosary is the oldest and most widely established Rosary association in the Church, traditionally under the care of the Dominican Order. Members commit to praying the full fifteen (now twenty) mysteries of the Rosary each week, not necessarily all at once. Blessed Alanus de Rupe revived the confraternity in the 15th century, and Pope St. Pius V formally established it after the victory at Lepanto in 1571, attributing the triumph to Our Lady of the Rosary. Enrollment is made through a Dominican priory or an authorized parish, and members share in the spiritual merits and indulgences of the entire Dominican Order. The confraternity also practices charity toward deceased members through Masses and prayers for the dead.",
