    body: "Taize prayer takes its name from the ecumenical monastic community founded by Brother Roger Schutz in Taize, France, in 1940. The prayer form is built around three elements: the singing of short, melodic refrains repeated many times (often in Latin or multiple languages), extended periods of silence, and the reading of Scripture. Candlelight, icons, and a meditative atmosphere characterize the gatherings. Though Taize is an ecumenical community, its prayer form has been widely adopted in Catholic parishes, especially for youth ministry, Advent and Lenten services, and evenings of reflection. Catholic bishops have generally welcomed Taize prayer as compatible with Catholic worship when properly conducted. The simplicity of the chants — often just a single Scripture verse set to music — allows participants to enter deeply into prayer without needing hymnals or musical training.",
