    tags: ["Mary", "procession", "public", "May", "October", "crowning"],
    oneLiner: "Public processions honoring the Blessed Virgin Mary, often featuring her statue carried through streets with hymns and prayers.",
    body: "Marian processions are public acts of devotion in which the faithful carry a statue or image of the Blessed Virgin Mary through the streets or church grounds, accompanied by hymns, the Rosary, and litanies. They are especially associated with May (the month of Mary), October (the month of the Rosary), and feasts such as the Assumption (August 15), the Immaculate Conception (December 8), and Our Lady of Fatima (May 13). In many cultures, these processions have deep local traditions: the Flores de Mayo in the Philippines, the processions of La Virgen del Carmen in Spain and Latin America, and May Crowning ceremonies in parishes throughout the English-speaking world. Marian processions are a form of public witness to Catholic faith and devotion, sanctifying the streets and neighborhoods through which they pass. The Second Vatican Council affirmed the legitimacy of such popular devotions when properly oriented toward the liturgy.",
    example: "On the feast of the Assumption, a parish in southern Italy carries a life-size statue of the Madonna through the town, pausing at homes where families have set up small altars with flowers and candles. The entire community joins in singing the Salve Regina as the procession returns to the church.",
    whyItMatters: "Marian processions bring the faith out of the church building and into the public square, sanctifying everyday spaces. They strengthen communal bonds, provide visible witness to the culture, and express the deeply human desire to honor the Mother of God with the whole body, not just the mind.",
