    term: "Morning Offering Devotion",
    category: "devotions",
    tags: ["morning", "offering", "apostleship", "prayer", "daily"],
    oneLiner: "The daily practice of offering all prayers, works, joys, and sufferings of the day to God through the Sacred Heart of Jesus.",
    body: "The Morning Offering is a brief prayer said upon waking by which the faithful consecrate the entire day — all its actions, joys, and sufferings — to God in union with the Holy Sacrifice of the Mass being offered throughout the world. The classic form was composed by the Apostleship of Prayer (now the Pope's Worldwide Prayer Network), founded by Jesuit Father Francois-Xavier Gautrelet in 1844. The prayer typically includes offering the day for the Holy Father's monthly intentions as well as personal intentions. Theologically, the Morning Offering flows from the baptismal priesthood of all believers, who are called to make their lives a 'living sacrifice' (Romans 12:1). By consciously offering the day's beginning, the faithful transform even ordinary activities — work, meals, conversations, and sufferings — into acts of worship and intercession.",
    example: "A Catholic begins each day by kneeling briefly and praying: 'O Jesus, through the Immaculate Heart of Mary, I offer You my prayers, works, joys, and sufferings of this day for all the intentions of Your Sacred Heart, in union with the Holy Sacrifice of the Mass throughout the world.'",
