    tags: ["Divine Mercy", "three o'clock", "Faustina", "Passion", "hour"],
    oneLiner: "A brief prayer at 3:00 PM, the Hour of Great Mercy, commemorating the moment of Christ's death on the Cross.",
    body: "The Three O'Clock Prayer, also called the Hour of Great Mercy, is a devotion rooted in the revelations of Jesus to St. Faustina Kowalska as recorded in her Diary. Jesus told Faustina: 'At three o'clock, implore My mercy, especially for sinners; and, if only for a brief moment, immerse yourself in My Passion, particularly in My abandonment at the moment of agony... In this hour I will refuse nothing to the soul that makes a request of Me in virtue of My Passion' (Diary, 1320). The practice involves pausing at 3:00 PM to meditate briefly on the Passion — particularly Christ's death — and to pray for mercy for oneself and the whole world. Catholics may pray the Chaplet of Divine Mercy, the Stations of the Cross, or simply a brief personal prayer at this hour. The devotion connects to the ancient tradition of the Church praying at the ninth hour (None).",
    example: "An office worker sets a daily alarm for 3:00 PM. When it sounds, she pauses for one minute, silently praying: 'You expired, Jesus, but the source of life gushed forth for souls, and the ocean of mercy opened up for the whole world. O Fount of Life, unfathomable Divine Mercy, envelop the whole world and empty Yourself out upon us.'",
    whyItMatters: "The Three O'Clock Prayer sanctifies the workday by anchoring it to the central event of salvation history. It cultivates a habit of remembering Christ's Passion and interceding for sinners at the very hour when mercy was poured out from the Cross.",
