    oneLiner: "Veneration of a 16th-century wax statue of the Child Jesus in Prague, associated with graces of provision and trust in divine providence.",
    body: "The Infant of Prague (Prazske Jezulatko) is a 19-inch wax-coated wooden statue of the Child Jesus, holding a globe surmounted by a cross in one hand and offering a blessing with the other. The statue was brought to Prague from Spain in 1556 and entrusted to the Discalced Carmelites in 1628. During the Thirty Years' War, the statue was damaged and abandoned, but Father Cyril of the Mother of God restored it after reportedly hearing the Christ Child say: 'Have mercy on Me, and I will have mercy on you. Give Me My hands, and I will give you peace.' Numerous miracles and graces of temporal provision have been attributed to the devotion. The Infant is dressed in elaborate vestments that change with the liturgical seasons — over 60 outfits exist, including garments donated by Empress Maria Theresa. Replicas of the statue are found in churches worldwide, and novenas to the Infant of Prague are widely prayed for financial needs, family concerns, and childlike trust in God.",
    example: "A novena to the Infant of Prague includes the prayer: 'O Jesus, who said, Ask and you shall receive, seek and you shall find, knock and it shall be opened to you, through the intercession of Mary, Your most holy Mother, I knock, I seek, I ask that my prayer be granted.' The devotion emphasizes that God cares for our material as well as spiritual needs.",
