    id: "devotions-daily-examination",
    term: "Daily Examination of Conscience",
    category: "devotions",
    tags: ["examination", "conscience", "Ignatian", "examen", "evening"],
    oneLiner: "A daily review of one's actions, thoughts, and dispositions before God, rooted in the Ignatian Examen tradition.",
    body: "The Daily Examination of Conscience (or Examen) is a structured reflection at the end of each day in which the faithful review their actions, thoughts, and attitudes in the light of God's presence and grace. The most influential form is the Ignatian Examen developed by St. Ignatius of Loyola, consisting of five steps: (1) gratitude — recalling blessings of the day; (2) petition — asking the Holy Spirit for light; (3) review — walking through the day's events, noting moments of consolation (closeness to God) and desolation (distance from God); (4) contrition — asking forgiveness for failures; and (5) resolution — looking ahead to tomorrow with renewed purpose. St. Ignatius considered the Examen so essential that even if a Jesuit could do no other prayer, he should do this one. The practice differs from examination of conscience before Confession (which focuses on sins) in that it equally attends to graces, movements of the Spirit, and patterns of growth.",
    example: "Before bed, a businessman spends ten minutes in the Examen. He recalls the unexpected kindness of a colleague (gratitude), recognizes his impatience in a meeting (contrition), and notices that he felt closest to God during a moment of service to an intern (consolation). He resolves to be more patient tomorrow.",
    whyItMatters: "The Daily Examination cultivates spiritual awareness and prevents the examined life from remaining merely philosophical. By daily reviewing one's movements toward and away from God, the faithful develop the habit of discernment that is essential for authentic Christian decision-making.",
