    oneLiner: "A dedicated space in the Catholic home set apart for prayer, containing sacred images, candles, and devotional objects.",
    body: "A prayer corner (also called a home altar, icon corner, or sacred space) is a designated area in a Catholic home set apart for personal and family prayer. Drawing on the Eastern Christian tradition of the 'beautiful corner' (krasny ugol) and the Western tradition of household shrines, a Catholic prayer corner typically includes a crucifix, an image or statue of the Blessed Virgin Mary, a Bible, holy water, blessed candles, a rosary, and images of the family's patron saints. Many families add liturgical-season decorations: an Advent wreath, a Nativity set, Lenten purple, or Easter lilies. The prayer corner serves as the spiritual heart of the domestic church, the place where the family gathers for morning and evening prayers, the Rosary, grace before meals, and individual devotions. The Catechism of the Catholic Church (CCC 2691) encourages families to have such a space, noting that it 'favors prayer in common.'",
