    body: "The Mission Rosary was created in 1951 by Venerable Archbishop Fulton J. Sheen, then National Director of the Society for the Propagation of the Faith in the United States. Each of the five decades is made of different-colored beads representing a continent: green for Africa, red for the Americas, white for Europe, blue for Oceania, and yellow for Asia. As the faithful pray each decade, they offer it for the intentions and missionary needs of that particular continent. The Mission Rosary was designed to make the universal mission of the Church concrete and personal. Sheen wrote: 'When you pray the Mission Rosary, you embrace the whole world in prayer.' The rosaries are distributed by the Pontifical Mission Societies and have become popular gifts for children and adults alike, visually reminding the pray-er that the Rosary is offered not only for personal intentions but for the evangelization of all peoples.",
