    body: "The Scriptural Rosary is a form of the Rosary in which a short passage from Sacred Scripture is read aloud before each of the ten Hail Marys in every decade, providing a specific biblical focus for each prayer. This means that each mystery is accompanied by ten Scripture verses that progressively unfold the event being contemplated. For example, during the first Sorrowful Mystery (the Agony in the Garden), the ten verses might include 'Jesus came with them to a place called Gethsemane' (Matthew 26:36), 'My soul is sorrowful even to death' (Matthew 26:38), and 'Father, if it is possible, let this cup pass from me' (Matthew 26:39). The practice responds to the concern that repetitive Hail Marys can become mechanical by providing rich, biblical content for meditation. The Scriptural Rosary has been published in various editions and is recommended by many spiritual directors as an excellent way to combine Marian devotion with deep immersion in the Word of God.",
    example: "A prayer group prays the Scriptural Rosary by using a booklet that provides ten Bible verses for each mystery. The leader reads a verse, the group responds with a Hail Mary, and the pattern continues. Members report that the Scripture verses transform their experience of the Rosary, making each Hail Mary a meditation rather than a recitation.",
